You've missed a lot of key points and information from this video. Firstly purchasing a house is a transaction. Generally one that requires lending. The Lender is generally the bank. To acquire this lending requires you to be credit worthy. Becoming credit worthy means proving that you are a low risk borrower who is likely to repay on time. To meet these requirements you need the following... A strong credit history, A history of managing debt responsibly, A stable income, And the initial deposit saved from your own (blood, sweat and tears). Only then will the bank look at you favourable for lending. Once all of these boxes have been ticked you are happy because now you can finally purchase a house! (Yippee) which leads us to answering your question. Wtf is the bank actually producing? The bank is producing credit to you and a Financial Asset to them. Basically a claim to future money from you. This all falls under the umbrella of how the economy works, so its not necessarily the banks fault that we want to live in our own homes 30 years before we can actually afford too, its ours. And the system has been put in place for this purpose. The alternative is you can always save up that $500,000 and pay for the house outright but by the time you get to saving that $500,000 the house is now valued at $900,000 lol.
